# Project Structure

NeuroAtlas AI is a research-phase Clinical Decision Support System for pediatric
neurorehabilitation. Code lives at the repository root (the project was flattened —
there is no longer a `neuroatlas-ai/` subdirectory).

> `ARCHITECTURE.md` describes a **proposed/future** layout
> (apps/, services/, pipelines/...). It is aspirational — the **actual** code
> follows the hexagonal layout below. Trust the code, not section 6 of that doc.

## Layout

```
<repo root>/
├── pyproject.toml          # Poetry, Python 3.12, dependency groups per service
├── Makefile                # run/test/lint entrypoints (see commands below)
├── infra/
│   ├── infra.compose.yml       # Postgres + Kafka + shared network (make up_infra)
│   ├── kafka/init_topics.py    # topic bootstrap from EventStream (make kafka_topics)
│   ├── application.compose.yml # app services (make up_app / up_<abbr>)
│   ├── .env                    # runtime config (Makefile + Docker Compose)
│   └── .env.example            # template only; `make init` copies to .env
└── src/
    ├── common/             # shared library used by every service
    │   ├── application/     # app_factory (FastAPI builder), logging, settings
    │   ├── core/            # Command/CommandResult base, exceptions, ports (uow, bus)
    │   ├── core/entities/   # EventStream, EventKind, Event
    │   ├── adapters/bus/    # Kafka + in-memory EventBus adapters
    │   └── http/            # error_handlers, ResponseSchema/ListResponseSchema
    ├── patients/           # clinical-data service (FastAPI, port 8001)
    ├── ml/                 # prediction service (FastAPI, port 8002; Kafka consumer)
    └── housekeeper/        # migrations & DB ops (FastAPI, port 8003)
```

## Service module pattern (hexagonal / ports & adapters)

Each service (`patients`, `ml`) follows the same structure:

```
<service>/
├── main.py             # builds app via common.application.app_factory.create(...)
├── lifespan.py         # startup/shutdown wiring of adapters
├── settings.py         # service-specific settings
├── domain/             # pure business logic, no framework imports
│   ├── entities.py      # dataclasses (e.g. Patient, Assessment)
│   ├── commands.py      # write use-cases (Command subclasses w/ nested Context)
│   ├── queries.py       # read use-cases
│   ├── exceptions.py
│   └── ports/           # abstract interfaces (repositories, uow, predictor)
├── adapters/           # concrete implementations of ports
│   ├── http/            # FastAPI router (handlers.py), schemas, dependencies
│   ├── database/        # repos / unit-of-work (e.g. in_mem.py)
│   └── predictor/       # ml-only: baseline.py
└── tests/              # mirrors source tree (test_domain/...)
```

## Conventions

- **Layering:** `adapters` depend on `domain`; `domain` never imports adapters or
  FastAPI. Cross-cutting concerns live in `common`.
- **Write path:** HTTP handler builds a `Command.Context`, runs `Command(uow, ctx).execute()`,
  returns `ResponseSchema`. Validation goes in `Context.validate_context()`.
- **Read path:** handler calls a function in `domain/queries.py` with the `uow`.
- **Persistence:** access via Unit of Work port (`domain/ports/uow.py`); current
  adapter is in-memory. IDs are ULID-based with prefixes (`pat_`, `asm_`).
- **Schemas:** Pydantic for HTTP I/O (`adapters/http/schemas.py`); domain uses dataclasses.
- **Tests:** pytest under `src/<service>/tests/`, mirroring the module path.

## Common commands (run from the repo root)

- `make up_infra` / `make down_infra` — Postgres + Kafka + shared Docker network
- `make kafka_topics` — bootstrap Kafka topics locally
- `make up_app` / `make down_app` — application services only
- `make up` / `make down` — full stack (infra + app)
- `make up_pat` / `make up_ml` / `make up_hk` — per-service app targets
- `make run_patients` / `make run_ml` — run a service locally (in-memory, no infra)
- `make test` / `make test_patients` / `make test_ml` — pytest
- `make lint` (ruff + mypy), `make fmt` (isort + ruff format), `make check` — fmt+lint+test
